# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bacnet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bacnet/ashrae] The **American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers** (**ASHRAE** /ˈæʃreɪ/ *ASH-ray*) is an American professional association seeking to advance heating, ventilation, air conditioning and refrigeration (HVAC&R) systems design and construction.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] ASHRAE has over 50,000 members in more than 130 countries worldwide.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] ASHRAE's members comprise building services engineers, architects, mechanical contractors, building owners, equipment manufacturers' employees, and others concerned with the design and construction of HVAC&R systems in buildings.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] The society funds research projects, offers continuing education programs, and develops and publishes technical standards to improve building services engineering, energy efficiency, indoor air quality, and sustainable development.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] ASHRAE was founded in 1894 at a meeting of engineers in New York City, formerly headquartered at 345 East 47th Street (the United Engineering Center), and has held an annual meeting since 1895.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] Until 1954 it was known as the American Society of Heating and Ventilating Engineers (ASHVE); in that year it changed its name to the American Society of Heating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHAE).
[src:bacnet/ashrae] Its current name and organization came from the 1959 merger of ASHAE and the American Society of Refrigerating Engineers (ASRE).
[src:bacnet/ashrae] Despite having 'American' in its name, ASHRAE is a global organization, holding international events.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] In 2012, it rebranded itself with a new logo and tagline: "Shaping Tomorrow's Built Environment Today".
[src:bacnet/ashrae] The ASHRAE Handbook is a four-volume resource for HVAC&R technology and is available in both print and electronic versions.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] The volumes are *Fundamentals*, *HVAC Applications*, *HVAC Systems and Equipment*, and *Refrigeration*.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] One of the four volumes is updated each year.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] ASHRAE also publishes a set of standards and guidelines relating to HVAC systems and issues, that are often referenced in building codes and used by consulting engineers, mechanical contractors, architects, and government agencies.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] These standards are periodically reviewed, revised and republished.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] The society also publishes two magazines: the *ASHRAE Journal* is issued monthly, and *High Performing Buildings Magazine* is published quarterly.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] They contain articles on related technology, information on upcoming meetings, editorials, and case studies of various well-performing buildings.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] ASHRAE also publishes books, *ASHRAE Transactions*, and the *International Journal of HVAC&R Research*.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] ASHRAE supported the Streamlining Energy Efficiency for Schools Act of 2014 (H.R.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] 4092; 113th Congress), a bill that would require the United States Department of Energy to establish a centralized clearinghouse to disseminate information on federal programs, incentives, and mechanisms for financing energy-efficient retrofits and upgrades at schools.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] ASHRAE offers six categories of awards: achievement awards to recognize personal honors; personal awards for general and specific society activities; paper awards; society awards for groups or chapters; chapters and regional awards.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] ASHRAE Fellow is a Membership Grade of Distinction conferred by The College of Fellows of ASHRAE, Inc. to an ASHRAE member with significant publications or innovations and distinguished scientific and engineering background in the fields of heating, refrigeration, air conditioning, ventilation.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] The ASHRAE Fellow membership grade is the highest elected grade in ASHRAE.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] ASHRAE has a Hall of Fame honoring "deceased members who have made milestone contributions to the growth of ASHRAE-related technology.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] To demonstrate the Society's commitment to sustainability, ASHRAE renovated its previous headquarters building in Atlanta, Ga.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] After the renovation and occupancy in June 2008, the building received many awards, including an Energy Star rating with a score of 95, a Platinum Certification from USGBC's LEED program, and four Green Globes from the Green Building Initiative.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] The current site energy use intensity (EUI) is 35.8 kBtu/Sqft (411 MJ/m2), a 60 percent reduction from the pre-renovation value.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] The renovation included the use of a dedicated outdoor air supply (DOAS) system with energy recovery and humidity control; a ground-source heat pump system; and variable refrigerant flow systems with heat recovery.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] The building also serves as a live case study.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] A web-based user interface allowed researchers around the world to extract data from the building to study factors such as energy use and electric power demand, water consumption and indoor air quality.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] In 2018, ASHRAE decided to move their world headquarters, settling on retrofitting a 1970s-era building in Peachtree Corners, suburban Atlanta.
[src:bacnet/ashrae] Completed in 2022, the building has been renovated to comply with ASHRAE's own standards, including ASHRAE 90.1, and the organization has the goal of operating the building at net-zero energy, powered by a large on-site solar array.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] BACnet was designed to allow communication of building automation and control systems for applications such as heating, ventilating, and air-conditioning control (HVAC), lighting control, access control, and fire detection systems and their associated equipment.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] The BACnet protocol provides mechanisms for computerized building automation devices to exchange information, regardless of the particular building service they perform.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] The development of the BACnet protocol began in June, 1987, in Nashville, Tennessee, at the inaugural meeting of the ASHRAE BACnet committee, known at that time as SPC 135P, "EMCS Message Protocol".
[src:bacnet/bacnet] The committee worked at reaching consensus using working groups to divide up the task of creating a standard.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] The working groups focused on specific areas and provided information and recommendations to the main committee.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] The first three working groups were the Data Type and Attribute Working Group, Primitive Data Format Working Group, and the Application Services Working Group.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] BACnet became ANSI/ASHRAE Standard 135 in 1995.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] BACnet had an almost immediate impact on the HVAC controls industry.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] In 1996 Alerton announced a BACnet product line for HVAC controls, from the operator's workstation to small variable air volume (VAV) controllers.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] Automated Logic Corporation and Delta Controls soon followed suit.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] The Method of Test for Conformance to BACnet was published in 2003 as BSR/ASHRAE Standard 135.1.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] BACnet became an international (ISO) standard as ISO 16484-5:2003.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] The Method of Test would soon follow as ISO 16484-6:2005.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] BACnet is under continuous maintenance by the ASHRAE Standing Standard Project Committee 135.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] On July 12, 2017, BACnet reached a milestone with the issuance of the 1000th Vendor ID.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] Vendor IDs are assigned by ASHRAE and are distributed internationally.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] Those vendor identifiers can be viewed at the BACnet website Archived 2009-11-21 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] Michael (Mike) Newman, Manager of the Computer Section of the Utilities and Energy Management Department at Cornell University, served as the BACnet committee chairman until June, 2000, when he was succeeded by his vice-chair of 13 years, Steven (Steve) Bushby from NIST.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] 2000–The BACnet Manufacturers’ Association (BMA) is formed and soon opens the BACnet Testing Laboratory.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] The first president of BMA is James Lee.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] BACnet is translated into Chinese and Japanese.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] BMA sponsors first BACnet Interoperability Workshop (“PlugFest”) at NIST with 12 organizations attending.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] (PlugFest-2012 had 49 teams.) BACnet Testing Laboratories (BTL) was formed and James Butler was a founding manager of BTL.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] During Steve Bushby's four-year term as committee chair the BACnet standard was republished twice, in 2001 and 2004, each time with new capabilities added to the standard.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] The 2001 version featured, among other things, extensions to support fire / life-safety systems.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] In June, 2004, 17 years after the first BACnet meeting and back in Nashville, William (Bill) Swan (a.k.a.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] "BACnet Bill") from Alerton began his four-year stint as committee chair.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] During his term the number of committee working groups grew to 11, pursuing areas such as support for lighting, access control, energy utility/building integration, and wireless communications.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] In January 2006 the BACnet Manufacturers Association and the BACnet Interest Group of North America combined their operation in a new organization called BACnet International Archived 2020-08-17 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] In June 2008, in Salt Lake City, Dave Robin from Automated Logic Corporation took over the reins as the new committee chair after serving 4 years as vice chair.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] During Dave's term, 22 addenda were published for the 135-2008 standard and republished as 135-2010.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] Several addenda were published for 135-2010 and the standard was republished as 135-2012.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] In June 2012, in San Antonio, Carl Neilson from Delta Controls took over the reins as the new committee chair after serving 4 years as vice chair.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] During Carl's term, 12 addenda were published for the 135-2012 standard and it was republished as 135-2016.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] Carl stepped down as chair in June 2015.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] In June 2015, Bernhard Isler, from Siemens, became chair after serving 3 years as vice chair and 4 years as secretary.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] During Bernhard's term, 10 addenda were published for the 135-2016 standard.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] One addendum to 135.1-2013 was also published.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] Bernhard stepped down as chair in June 2018.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] In June 2018, Michael Osborne from Reliable Controls, became chair after serving 3 years as secretary and 3 years as vice chair.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] The BACnet protocol defines a number of services that are used to communicate between building devices.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] The protocol services include Who-Is, I-Am, Who-Has, I-Have, which are used for Device and Object discovery.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] Services such as Read-Property and Write-Property are used for data sharing.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] As of ANSI/ASHRAE 135-2016, the BACnet protocol defines 60 object types that are acted upon by the services.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] The BACnet protocol defines a number of data link and physical layers, including ARCNET, Ethernet, BACnet/IP, BACnet/IPv6, BACnet/MSTP, point-to-point over RS-232, multidrop serial bus with token passing over RS-485, Zigbee, and LonTalk.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] BACnet Testing Laboratories ("BTL") was established by BACnet International to test products to BACnet standards and support compliance testing and interoperability testing activities and consists of BTL Manager and the BTL working group ("BTL-WG").
[src:bacnet/bacnet] The BTL also provides testing services through BACnet Laboratories.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] The BTL Managers and BTL working groups of BACnet International administer the test Laboratories.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] All BTL-recognized BACnet Test Organizations are ISO 17025 accredited.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] In January, 2017, a new BTL certification program was announced.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] Under this program, the work of the BTL and WSPCert (the European BACnet certification body) is merged.
[src:bacnet/bacnet] This merger forms a single point of testing for both the BTL Mark and the Certificate of Conformance.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] BAS functionality may keep a building's climate within a specified range, provide light to rooms based on occupancy, monitor performance and device failures, and provide malfunction alarms to building maintenance staff.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] A BAS works to reduce building energy and maintenance costs compared to a non-controlled building.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Most commercial, institutional, and industrial buildings built after 2000 include a BAS, whilst older buildings may be retrofitted with a new BAS.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] A building controlled by a BAS is often referred to as an "intelligent building", a "smart building", or (if a residence) a *smart home*.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Commercial and industrial buildings have historically relied on robust proven protocols (like BACnet) while proprietary protocols (like X-10) were used in homes.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] With the advent of wireless sensor networks and the Internet of Things, an increasing number of smart buildings are resorting to using low-power wireless communication technologies such as Zigbee, Bluetooth Low Energy and LoRa to interconnect the local sensors, actuators and processing devices.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Almost all multi-story green buildings are designed to accommodate a BAS for the energy, air and water conservation characteristics.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Electrical device demand response is a typical function of a BAS, as is the more sophisticated ventilation and humidity monitoring required of "tight" insulated buildings.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Most green buildings also use as many low-power DC devices as possible.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Even a passivhaus design intended to consume no net energy whatsoever will typically require a BAS to manage heat capture, shading and venting, and scheduling device use.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Building management systems are most commonly implemented in large projects with extensive mechanical, HVAC, and electrical systems.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Systems linked to a BMS typically represent 40% of a building's energy usage; if lighting is included, this number approaches to 70%.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] BMS systems are a critical component to managing energy demand.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Improperly configured BMS systems are believed to account for 20% of building energy usage, or approximately 8% of total energy usage in the United States.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] In addition to controlling the building's internal environment, BMS systems are sometimes linked to access control (turnstiles and access doors controlling who is allowed access and egress to the building) or other security systems such as closed-circuit television (CCTV) and motion detectors.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Fire alarm systems and elevators are also sometimes linked to a BMS for monitoring.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] In case a fire is detected then only the fire alarm panel could close dampers in the ventilation system to stop smoke spreading, shut down air handlers, start smoke evacuation fans, and send all the elevators to the ground floor and park them to prevent people from using them.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Building management systems have also included disaster-response mechanisms (such as base isolation) to save structures from earthquakes.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] In more recent times, companies and governments have been working to find similar solutions for flood zones and coastal areas at-risk to rising sea levels.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Self-adjusting floating environment draws from existing technologies used to float concrete bridges and runways such as Washington's SR 520 and Japan's Mega-Float.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Analog inputs are used to read a variable measurement.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Examples are temperature, humidity and pressure sensors which could be thermistor, 4–20 mA, 0–10 volt or platinum resistance thermometer (resistance temperature detector), or wireless sensors.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] A digital input indicates a device is on or off.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Some examples of digital inputs would be a door contact switch, a current switch, an air flow switch, or a voltage-free relay contact (dry contact).
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Digital inputs could also be pulse inputs counting the pulses over a period of time.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] An example is a turbine flow meter transmitting flow data as a frequency of pulses to an input.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Nonintrusive load monitoring is software relying on digital sensors and algorithms to discover appliance or other loads from electrical or magnetic characteristics of the circuit.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] It is however detecting the event by an analog means.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] These are extremely cost-effective in operation and useful not only for identification but to detect start-up transients, line or equipment faults, etc.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Occupancy sensors detect the presence, number, and sometimes location of people in a space to enable demand-controlled systems for lighting, HVAC, and energy management.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Traditional examples include passive infrared (PIR), ultrasonic, and CO2-based detectors, but advanced systems use low-resolution thermal imaging or area sensors to provide zone-level accuracy without capturing identifiable images, ensuring privacy compliance (e.g., GDPR).
[src:bacnet/building-automation] These sensors output analog heat signatures or digital counts that integrate with building management systems via protocols like BACnet or wireless IoT networks, reducing energy use by up to 40% through precise ventilation and lighting control.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Analog outputs control the speed or position of a device, such as a variable frequency drive, an I-P (current to pneumatics) transducer, or a valve or damper actuator.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] An example is a hot water valve opening up 25% to maintain a setpoint.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Another example is a variable frequency drive ramping up a motor slowly to avoid a hard start.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Digital outputs are used to open and close relays and switches as well as drive a load upon command.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] An example would be to turn on the parking lot lights when a photocell indicates it is dark outside.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Another example would be to open a valve by allowing 24VDC/AC to pass through the output powering the valve.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Analog outputs could also be pulse type outputs emitting a frequency of pulses over a given period of time.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] An example is an energy meter calculating kWh and emitting a frequency of pulses accordingly.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Controllers are essentially small, purpose-built computers with input and output capabilities.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] These controllers come in a range of sizes and capabilities to control devices commonly found in buildings, and to control sub-networks of controllers.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Inputs allow a controller to read temperature, humidity, pressure, current flow, air flow, and other essential factors.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] The outputs allow the controller to send command and control signals to slave devices, and to other parts of the system.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Inputs and outputs can be either digital or analog.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Digital outputs are also sometimes called discrete depending on manufacturer.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Controllers used for building automation can be grouped in three categories: programmable logic controllers (PLCs), system/network controllers, and terminal unit controllers.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] However an additional device can also exist in order to integrate third-party systems (e.g. a stand-alone AC system) into a central building automation system.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Terminal unit controllers usually are suited for control of lighting and/or simpler devices such as a package rooftop unit, heat pump, VAV box, fan coil, etc.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] The installer typically selects one of the available pre-programmed personalities best suited to the device to be controlled, and does not have to create new control logic.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Occupancy is one of two or more operating modes for a building automation system; unoccupied, morning warmup, and night-time setback are other common modes.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Occupancy is usually based on time of day schedules.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] In occupancy mode, the BAS aims to provides a comfortable climate and adequate lighting, often with zone-based control so that users on one side of a building have a different thermostat (or a different system, or sub system) than users on the opposite side.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] A temperature sensor in the zone provides feedback to the controller, so it can deliver heating or cooling as needed.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] If enabled, morning warmup (MWU) mode occurs prior to occupancy.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] During morning warmup the BAS tries to bring the building to setpoint just in time for occupancy.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] The BAS often factors in outdoor conditions and historical experience to optimize MWU.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] This is also referred to as *optimized start*.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Some buildings rely on occupancy sensors to activate lighting or climate conditioning.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Given the potential for long lead times before a space becomes sufficiently cool or warm, climate conditioning is not often initiated directly by an occupancy sensor.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Lighting can be turned on, off, or dimmed with a building automation or lighting control system based on time of day, or on occupancy sensor, photosensors and timers.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] One typical example is to turn the lights in a space on for a half-hour since the last motion was sensed.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] A photocell placed outside a building can sense darkness, and the time of day, and modulate lights in outer offices and the parking lot.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Lighting is also a good candidate for demand response, with many control systems providing the ability to dim (or turn off) lights to take advantage of DR incentives and savings.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] In newer buildings, the lighting control can be based on the field bus Digital Addressable Lighting Interface (DALI).
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Lamps with DALI ballasts are fully dimmable.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] DALI can also detect lamp and ballast failures on DALI luminaires and signals failures.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Shading and glazing are essential components in the building system, they affect occupants' visual, acoustical, and thermal comfort and provide the occupant with a view outdoor.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Automated shading and glazing systems are solutions for controlling solar heat gains and glare.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] It refers to the use of technology to control external or internal shading devices (such as blinds, and shades) or glazing itself.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] The system has an active and rapid response to various changing outdoor data (such as solar, wind) and to changing interior environment (such as temperature, illuminance, and occupant demands).
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Building shading and glazing systems can contribute to thermal and lighting improvement from both energy conservation and comfort point of view.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Dynamic shading devices allow the control of daylight and solar energy to enter into built environment in relation to outdoor conditions, daylighting demands and solar positions.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] The common products include venetian blinds, roller shades, louvers, and shutters.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] They are mostly installed on the interior side of the glazing system because of the low maintenance cost, but also can be used on the exterior or a combination of both.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Most air handlers mix return and outside air so less temperature/humidity conditioning is needed.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] This can save money by using less chilled or heated water (not all AHUs use chilled or hot water circuits).
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Some external air is needed to keep the building's air healthy.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] To optimize energy efficiency while maintaining healthy indoor air quality (IAQ), demand control (or controlled) ventilation (DCV) adjusts the amount of outside air based on measured levels of occupancy.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Analog or digital temperature sensors may be placed in the space or room, the return and supply air ducts, and sometimes the external air.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Actuators are placed on the hot and chilled water valves, the outside air and return air dampers.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] The supply fan (and return if applicable) is started and stopped based on either time of day, temperatures, building pressures or a combination.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] All modern building automation systems have alarm capabilities.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] It does little good to detect a potentially hazardous or costly situation if no one who can solve the problem is notified.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Notification can be through a computer (email or text message), pager, cellular phone voice call, audible alarm, or all of these.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] For insurance and liability purposes all systems keep logs of who was notified, when and how.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Alarms may immediately notify someone or only notify when alarms build to some threshold of seriousness or urgency.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] At sites with several buildings, momentary power failures can cause hundreds or thousands of alarms from equipment that has shut down – these should be suppressed and recognized as symptoms of a larger failure.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Some sites are programmed so that critical alarms are automatically re-sent at varying intervals.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] For example, a repeating critical alarm (of an uninterruptible power supply in 'bypass') might resound at 10 minutes, 30 minutes, and every 2 to 4 hours thereafter until the alarms are resolved.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Security systems can be interlocked to a building automation system.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] If occupancy sensors are present, they can also be used as burglar alarms.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Because security systems are often deliberately sabotaged, at least some detectors or cameras should have battery backup and wireless connectivity and the ability to trigger alarms when disconnected.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Modern systems typically use power-over-Ethernet (which can operate a pan-tilt-zoom camera and other devices up to 30–90 watts) which is capable of charging such batteries and keeps wireless networks free for genuinely wireless applications, such as backup communication in outage.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Fire alarm panels and their related smoke alarm systems are usually hard-wired to override building automation.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] For example: if the smoke alarm is activated, all the outside air dampers close to prevent air coming into the building, and an exhaust system can isolate the blaze.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Similarly, electrical fault detection systems can turn entire circuits off, regardless of the number of alarms this triggers or persons this distresses.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Fossil fuel combustion devices also tend to have their own over-rides, such as natural gas feed lines that turn off when slow pressure drops are detected (indicating a leak), or when excess methane is detected in the building's air supply.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] ASHRAE's open protocol BACnet or the open protocol LonTalk specify how most such devices interoperate.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Modern systems use SNMP to track events, building on decades of history with SNMP-based protocols in the computer networking world.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Physical connectivity between devices was historically provided by dedicated optical fiber, ethernet, ARCNET, RS-232, RS-485 or a low-bandwidth special purpose wireless network.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Modern systems rely on standards-based multi-protocol heterogeneous networking such as that specified in the IEEE 1905.1 standard and verified by the nVoy auditing mark.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Proprietary hardware dominates the controller market.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Each company has controllers for specific applications.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Some are designed with limited controls and no interoperability, such as simple packaged roof top units for HVAC.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Software will typically not integrate well with packages from other vendors.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Cooperation is at the Zigbee/BACnet/LonTalk level only.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Current systems provide interoperability at the application level, allowing users to mix-and-match devices from different manufacturers, and to provide integration with other compatible building control systems.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] These typically rely on SNMP, long used for this same purpose to integrate diverse computer networking devices into one coherent network.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] With the growing spectrum of capabilities and connections to the Internet of Things, building automation systems were repeatedly reported to be vulnerable, allowing hackers and cybercriminals to attack their components.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Buildings can be exploited by hackers to measure or change their environment: sensors allow surveillance (e.g. monitoring movements of employees or habits of inhabitants) while actuators allow to perform actions in buildings (e.g. opening doors or windows for intruders).
[src:bacnet/building-automation] Several vendors and committees started to improve the security features in their products and standards, including KNX, Zigbee and BACnet (see recent standards or standard drafts).
[src:bacnet/building-automation] However, researchers report several open problems in building automation security.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] On November 11, 2019, a 132-page security research paper was released titled "I Own Your Building (Management System)" by Gjoko Krstic and Sipke Mellema that addressed more than 100 vulnerabilities affecting various BMS and access control solutions by various vendors.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] On November 24, 2025, a 161-page security research paper was released titled "Project Brainfog: Beyond the Facade - Exposing Smart Giants" by Gjoko Krstic that addressed more than 1000 vulnerabilities affecting two widely used BAS controllers by ABB Group.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] It is common for room automation systems to employ a touchscreen as the primary way of controlling each operation.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] On November 27, 2018, a 29-page research paper titled "A Scalable Room Occupancy Prediction with Transferable Time Series Decomposition of CO2 Sensor Data" was published by Irvan Bastian Arief, Margaret Hamilton, and Flora Salim.
[src:bacnet/building-automation] The paper introduced a novel approach to leveraging carbon dioxide (CO2) sensor data to predict room occupancy—enabling smarter building automation by estimating the number of occupants in a room at any given time.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] Central controllers and most terminal unit controllers are programmable, meaning the direct digital control program code may be customized for the intended use.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] The program features include time schedules, setpoints, controllers, logic, timers, trend logs, and alarms.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] The unit controllers typically have analog and digital inputs, that allow measurement of the variable (temperature, humidity, or pressure) and analog and digital outputs for control of the medium (hot/cold water and/or steam).
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] Digital inputs are typically (dry) contacts from a control device, and analog inputs are typically a voltage or current measurement from a variable (temperature, humidity, velocity, or pressure) sensing device.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] Digital outputs are typically relay contacts used to start and stop equipment, and analog outputs are typically voltage or current signals to control the movement of the medium (air/water/steam) control devices.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] An early example of a direct digital control system was completed by the Australian business Midac in 1981-1982 using R-Tec Australian designed hardware.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] The system installed at the University of Melbourne used a serial communications network, connecting campus buildings back to a control room "front end" system in the basement of the Old Geology building.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] Each remote or Satellite Intelligence Unit (SIU) ran 2 Z80 microprocessors whilst the front end ran eleven Z80's in a Parallel Processing configuration with paged common memory.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] The z80 microprocessors shared the load by passing tasks to each other via the common memory and the communications network.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] This was possibly the first successful implementation of a distributed processing direct digital control.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] When direct digital controllers are networked together they can share information through a data bus.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] The control system may speak 'proprietary' or 'open protocol' language to communicate on the data bus.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] Examples of open protocol language are Building Automation Control Network (BACnet), LonWorks (Echelon), Modbus TCP and KNX.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] When different direct digital control data networks are linked together they can be controlled from a shared platform.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] This platform can then share information from one language to another.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] For example, a LON controller could share a temperature value with a BACnet controller.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] The integration platform can not only make information shareable, but can interact with all the devices.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] Most of the integration platforms are either a PC or a network appliance.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] In many cases, the HMI (human machine interface) or SCADA (Supervisory Control And Data Acquisition) are part of it.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] Integration platform examples, to name only a few, are the Tridium Niagara AX, Trend Controls, TAC Vista, CAN2GO and the Unified Architecture i.e.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] OPC (Open Connectivity) server technology used when direct connectivity is not possible.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] Direct digital control is often used to control heating, ventilating, and air conditioning devices such as valves via microprocessors using software to perform the control logic.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] Such systems receive analog and digital inputs from the sensors and devices and, according to the control logic, provide analog or digital outputs.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] These systems may be mated with a software package that graphically allows operators to monitor, control, alarm and diagnose building equipment remotely.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] Direct digital control can be applied to optimize plant growth in a growth chamber.
[src:bacnet/direct-digital-control] Using an algorithm based on optimal control theory, it is possible to control the speed of an induction motor using a microcontroller.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] The first HVAC controllers utilized pneumatic controls since engineers understood fluid control.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] Thus, the properties of steam and air were used to control the flow of heated or cooled air via mechanically controlled logic.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] After the control of air flow and temperature was standardized, the use of electromechanical relays in ladder logic to switch dampers became standardized.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] Eventually, the relays became electronic switches, as transistors eventually could handle greater current loads.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] By 1985, pneumatic controls could no longer compete with this new technology although pneumatic control systems (sometimes decades old) are still common in many older buildings.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] By the year 2000, computerized controllers were common.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] Today, some of these controllers can even be accessed by web browsers, which need no longer be in the same building as the HVAC equipment.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] This allows some economies of scale, as a single operations center can easily monitor multiple buildings.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] Prior to about the late 1960s, HVAC systems were controlled by pneumatics (using air pressure and tubes to move valves and dampers).
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] Then, digital computerization began to replace those systems.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] Central controllers and most terminal unit controllers are programmable, meaning the direct digital control (DDC) program code may be customized for the intended use.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] The program features include time schedules, set points, controllers, logic, timers, trend logs, and alarms.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] The unit controllers typically have analog and digital inputs that allow measurement of the variable (temperature, humidity, or pressure) and analog and digital outputs for control of the transport medium (hot/cold water and/or steam).
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] Digital outputs are typically relay contacts used to start and stop equipment, and analog outputs are typically voltage or current signals to control the movement of the medium (air/water/steam) control devices such as valves, dampers, and motors.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] Groups of DDC controllers, networked or not, form a layer of systems themselves.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] This "subsystem" is vital to the performance and basic operation of the overall HVAC system.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] The DDC system is the "brain" of the HVAC system.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] It dictates the position of every damper and valve in a system.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] It determines which fans, pumps, and chiller run and at what speed or capacity.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] With this configurable intelligence in this "brain", we are moving to the concept of building automation.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] More complex HVAC systems can interface with a Building Automation System (BAS) to allow the building owners to have more control over the heating or cooling units.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] The building owner can monitor the system and respond to alarms generated by the system from local or remote locations.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] The system can be scheduled for occupancy or the configuration can be changed from the BAS.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] Sometimes the BAS is directly controlling the HVAC components.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] Depending on the BAS different interfaces can be used.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] Today, there are also dedicated gateways that connect advanced VRV / VRF and Split HVAC Systems with Home Automation and BMS (Building Management Systems) controllers for centralized control and monitoring, obviating the need to purchase more complex and expensive HVAC systems.
[src:bacnet/hvac-control-system] In addition, such gateway solutions are capable of providing remote control operation of all HVAC indoor units over the internet.
